{"type": "assistant", "message": {"id": "msg_1783322042470", "type": "message", "role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "tool_use", "id": "chatcmpl-tool-8049fde3795bad95", "name": "Bash", "input": {"command": "cd /tmp && python3 -c \"\nimport re\nhtml = open('paper_2607_00777.html').read()\n# abstract\nm = re.search(r'<blockquote class=\\\"abstract[^>]*>(.*?)</blockquote>', html, re.DOTALL)\nif m:\n    txt = re.sub(r'<[^>]+>', '', m.group(1))\n    print('ABSTRACT:'); print(txt.strip()); print()\n# subjects\nm = re.search(r'<td class=\\\"tablecell subjects\\\"[^>]*>(.*?)</td>', html, re.DOTALL)\nif m:\n    print('SUBJECTS:', re.sub(r'<[^>]+>',' ',m.group(1)).strip())\n# comments\nm = re.search(r'<td class=\\\"tablecell comments\\\"[^>]*>(.*?)</td>', html, re.DOTALL)\nif m:\n    print('COMMENTS:', re.sub(r'<[^>]+>',' ',m.group(1)).strip())\n# DOI / cite\nm = re.search(r'<td class=\\\"tablecell arxivid\\\"[^>]*>(.*?)</td>', html, re.DOTALL)\nif m:\n    print('ARXIVID:', re.sub(r'<[^>]+>',' ',m.group(1)).strip())\n\"\necho \"---PDF URL---\"\ngrep -oE 'href=\\\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2607[^\\\"]+\\\"' paper_2607_00777.html | head -3", "description": "Parse abstract from arXiv HTML"}}], "model": "GLM-5.2-w4a8", "stop_reason": null, "stop_sequence": null, "usage": {"input_tokens": 0, "output_tokens": 0, "cache_creation_input_tokens": 0, "cache_read_input_tokens": 0}, "context_management": null}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "df8299e0-1bfd-46ef-86c6-0c06185e520d", "uuid": "da22827c-c931-4556-9ee6-b116a4295c92"}
{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-8049fde3795bad95", "type": "tool_result", "content": "ABSTRACT:\nAbstract:Recognizing jazz standards from audio is a challenging form of tune-level music retrieval: different performances of the same standard may vary in tempo, key, arrangement, instrumentation, improvisational content, and even whether the head melody is present. We study this problem using a curated subset of the Jazz Trio Database designed for cross-performance standard recognition. We compare a from-scratch trained Harmonic CNN baseline against frozen pretrained music representations from recent music understanding foundation models, using both supervised probing and nearest-neighbor retrieval. Our results suggest that from-scratch spectrogram models overfit strongly to training performances, while pretrained embeddings provide better top-$k$ results but are sensitive to performer identity, which can be partially reduced with a lightweight contrastive projection. Our findings motivate jazz standard recognition as a useful stress test for music representation models and as a step toward retrieval-based standard identification. Project page: this https URL.\n\nSUBJECTS: Sound (cs.SD) ; Machine Learning (cs.LG)\nARXIVID: arXiv:2607.00777  [cs.SD]\n---PDF URL---\nShell cwd was reset to /inspire/qb-ilm/project/video-generation/chenxie-25019/hyr/iHateTheWorld555.github.io", "is_error": false}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "df8299e0-1bfd-46ef-86c6-0c06185e520d", "uuid": "eef53c37-97dd-404c-ae1f-50f9a2faaffa", "timestamp": "2026-07-06T07:14:13.333Z", "tool_use_result": {"stdout": "ABSTRACT:\nAbstract:Recognizing jazz standards from audio is a challenging form of tune-level music retrieval: different performances of the same standard may vary in tempo, key, arrangement, instrumentation, improvisational content, and even whether the head melody is present. We study this problem using a curated subset of the Jazz Trio Database designed for cross-performance standard recognition. We compare a from-scratch trained Harmonic CNN baseline against frozen pretrained music representations from recent music understanding foundation models, using both supervised probing and nearest-neighbor retrieval. Our results suggest that from-scratch spectrogram models overfit strongly to training performances, while pretrained embeddings provide better top-$k$ results but are sensitive to performer identity, which can be partially reduced with a lightweight contrastive projection. Our findings motivate jazz standard recognition as a useful stress test for music representation models and as a step toward retrieval-based standard identification. Project page: this https URL.\n\nSUBJECTS: Sound (cs.SD) ; Machine Learning (cs.LG)\nARXIVID: arXiv:2607.00777  [cs.SD]\n---PDF URL---", "stderr": "\nShell cwd was reset to /inspire/qb-ilm/project/video-generation/chenxie-25019/hyr/iHateTheWorld555.github.io", "interrupted": false, "isImage": false, "noOutputExpected": false}}
